---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Setting Up Your Home Recording Studio — Blog" description="Build a professional studio on any budget with essential equipment and techniques">
  <!-- Article Header -->
  <section class="relative min-h-[50vh] w-full text-white pt-32 pb-16 overflow-hidden">
    <img 
      src="/assets/services/recording.png" 
      alt="Home Studio Setup" 
      class="absolute inset-0 w-full h-full object-cover"
      loading="eager"
    />
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-r from-black/80 via-black/70 to-black/50"></div>
    
    <div class="relative z-10 max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-16 pt-12">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <span class="inline-block px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold bg-[#D234C7]/20 text-[#D234C7] rounded-full">
          Equipment
        </span>
        <span class="text-sm text-gray-300">December 20, 2025</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-4">Setting Up Your Home Recording Studio</h1>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-gray-200">
        <span>By Tech Expert</span>
        <span>•</span>
        <span>10 min read</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article Content -->
  <section class="py-20 px-6 md:px-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-lg">
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
        Building a home recording studio doesn't require massive investment or professional space. With smart choices and proper setup, you can create a professional-quality recording environment in your bedroom, basement, or spare room. Here's everything you need to know.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">1. Choose Your Space Wisely</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Avoid rooms with parallel walls, which create flutter echo. Smaller rooms are often better than large ones—they're easier to treat acoustically. Choose a quiet room away from traffic noise, HVAC systems, and external sounds. If noise is unavoidable, plan extra acoustic treatment.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">2. Essential Equipment</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        A basic home studio requires:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 mb-6 space-y-2">
        <li>Computer with adequate processing power</li>
        <li>Audio interface (USB or Thunderbolt)</li>
        <li>Studio monitors or quality headphones</li>
        <li>Microphone with pop filter</li>
        <li>XLR cables and mic stand</li>
        <li>DAW software</li>
        <li>Plugins and virtual instruments</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">3. Acoustic Treatment</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        This is where most home studios fail. Bare rooms sound terrible for recording. Invest in acoustic panels for wall treatment, bass traps for corners, and bass superchunks to control low frequencies. You don't need expensive materials—strategically placed blankets, curtains, and foam can work effectively.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">4. Microphone Selection</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Don't scrimp on microphones. A good microphone can last decades and significantly impacts quality. Large-diaphragm condensers are versatile for vocals and instruments. Consider USB mics for simplicity or XLR mics for professional quality and flexibility.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">5. Monitoring Setup</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Accurate monitoring is crucial. Position monitors at ear level in an equilateral triangle from your listening position. Treat your sweet spot with absorption to minimize reflections. At minimum, listen on headphones too to verify mixes translate.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">6. Cable Management</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Proper cables reduce noise and interference. Use balanced XLR cables for audio connections, quality USB cables for interfaces, and power conditioners to protect equipment. Good cable management also makes troubleshooting easier.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">7. Software and Plugins</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Choose a DAW that fits your workflow and budget. Options range from free (Reaper trial, GarageBand) to premium (Pro Tools, Logic Pro). Build a plugin collection strategically—you don't need hundreds, just essential tools: compressor, EQ, reverb, and delay.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">Budget Considerations</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Start at $500-1000 for a basic setup and expand gradually. Prioritize:
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-gray-700 mb-6 space-y-2">
        <li>Good microphone ($200-500)</li>
        <li>Quality audio interface ($150-300)</li>
        <li>Acoustic treatment ($200-400)</li>
        <li>Headphones ($100-200)</li>
        <li>Cables and accessories ($50-100)</li>
      </ol>

      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
        A professional home studio is absolutely achievable. Start with quality fundamentals, add gear gradually, and focus on skill development. Many Grammy-winning albums have been recorded in home studios. What matters most is your dedication and technique.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Author Info -->
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
        <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-r from-[#D234C7] to-[#32BEF1]"></div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Tech Expert</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600">Audio engineer specializing in home studio setup and optimization.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Navigation -->
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-12 pt-12 border-t border-gray-200">
      <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
        <a href="/blog/mixing-mistakes" class="text-[#D234C7] font-semibold hover:underline">← Previous Article</a>
        <a href="/blog" class="text-[#D234C7] font-semibold hover:underline">Back to Blog</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
